<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,362,388]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Diagnoses.</emphasis>
Nymphs: 1) Frontal keel absent; 2) lingua broadly pointed apically; 3) glossa 0.6x length of paraglossa, 4) apex of paraglossa with rows of pectinate setae; 5) segment II of labial palp with a small distomedial projection; 6) posterior margin of abdominal terga with rounded spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
Male imago: 1) turbinate eyes anteriorly divergent and widely separated from each other, upper surface ellipsoidal (
<figureCitation box="[291,381,512,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); 2) terga light whitish brown, lateral margins darker (
<figureCitation box="[1030,1175,512,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Figs. 14, 15</figureCitation>
); 3) forceps with first segment constricted medioapically (
<figureCitation box="[589,680,549,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
); 4) posterior margin of subgenital plate with a small rounded projection (
<figureCitation box="[285,372,586,612]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
); 5) length of body relatively small (4.0 mm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,523,623,649]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Description (Male imago).</emphasis>
Measurements. Body 4.0 mm; forewing 4.0– 
<quantity box="[1054,1146,624,650]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="4.3">4.3 mm</quantity>
; antenna 
<quantity box="[1255,1348,624,650]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
; tibia I: 
<quantity box="[151,258,661,687]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.31" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="1.31">1.31 mm</quantity>
; tibia II: 
<quantity box="[365,472,661,687]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.8" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.88">0.88 mm</quantity>
; tibia III: 
<quantity box="[589,696,661,687]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.89">0.89 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis box="[197,263,698,723]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[283,435,698,724]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Figs. 14–15</figureCitation>
). Coloration light brown with V shaped brown mark between compound eyes. Turbinate portion of compound eyes orangish; basal half of stalk brown, paler toward apex. Antenna light brown. Dorsal portion of turbinate eyes ellipsoidal; length 1.5x width; stalk height 0.5x width of dorsal portion; inner margins widely separated, divergent anteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis box="[197,283,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Thorax</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[301,446,848,874]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Figs. 14–15</figureCitation>
). Pro, meso and metanotum brown; submedioscutum light brown; scutellum dark brown. Sternum brown. Anteronotal protuberance rounded. Metascutellar protuberance pointed dorsally. Legs whitish. Leg I: tibia 1.7x length of femur; tarsi 1.6x length of femur; and with 4 segments decreasing on length apically. Leg II and III: tibia 1.4x length of femur; tarsi 0.4x length of femur. Forewing (
<figureCitation box="[1223,1323,960,986]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Figs. 16</figureCitation>
) hyaline, posterior region of costal and subcostal veins grayish; veins Costal and subcostal light brown; stigmatic area with 6 cross veins not touching subcostal vein; marginal intercalary paired, except single between veins ICu1 and A; length of intercalary vein between IMA and IMA2 1.7x distance between adjacent longitudinal veins; length of forewing about 2.4x width.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis box="[197,309,1147,1172]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[326,471,1146,1172]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Figs. 14–15</figureCitation>
). Terga light whitish brown, lateral margins darker; tracheation blackish. Sterna light whitish brown. Genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[524,622,1184,1210]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,269,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[193,1392,213,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-33@8.[178,1409,194,1897]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Americabaetis labiosus. Male imago. 14. Lateral view; 15. Dorsal view; 16. Forewing; 17. Genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302615/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Figs. 17</figureCitation>
) segment I whitish washed with brown, segments II and III whitish. Forceps segment I distinctly constricted medioapically; 0,5x length of segment II; distance between base of forceps 0,2x distance between lateral margins of forceps. Forceps segment II narrow submedially. Forceps segment III elongate, 2.7x as long as wide; 0.17x length of segment II. Posterior margin of subgenital plate with a small rounded projection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,362,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,345,1370,1396]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Comments.</emphasis>
In 
<collectingCountry box="[390,466,1370,1396]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Brazil</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[475,614,1371,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="labiosus">
<emphasis box="[475,614,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">A. labiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently restricted to the southern area of the country. Their nymphs, as those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[397,517,1408,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="titthion">
<emphasis box="[397,517,1408,1433]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">A. titthion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Salles &amp; Raimundi &amp; Boldrini &amp; Souza-Franco, 2010" authorityName="Salles &amp; Raimundi &amp; Boldrini &amp; Souza-Franco" authorityYear="2010" box="[576,794,1408,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mecistognathus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[576,794,1408,1433]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">A. mecistognathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,906,1407,1433]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[810,906,1407,1433]" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, inhabit shallow areas with moderate to fast current (
<figureCitation box="[250,339,1445,1471]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–30" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1396,1420]" captionTargetBox="[176,1411,433,1370]" captionTargetId="figure-252@10.[170,1417,421,1375]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 27–30. General aspect of Americabaetis nymphs’ habitat. 27. A. mecistognathus, sp. nov.; 28. A. alphus and A. longetron; 29. A. labiosus; 30. A. titthion." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302619/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="23">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). However, unlike these species, they are often associated with dead leaves above rocks. The altitudinal range of this species varies from 
<quantity box="[664,841,1482,1508]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="23" unit="m" value="1300.0" valueMax="1900.0" valueMin="700.0">700 to 1900 m</quantity>
.a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
